(7061, 1, '2018-05-31 15:13:20', '2018-05-31 19:13:20', '<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;"><img class="size-full wp-image-6981 alignleft" src="http://leasepilot.dev.cc/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/bbair.jpeg" alt="" width="224" height="224" />What’s your role at LeasePilot? </span></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Marketing. My role is to spread the good word about what we’re doing here, to create enthusiasm and action around the value we create, and ultimately, to make the sales team’s job as simple and streamlined as possible.</span>\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">What type of work were you doing before LeasePilot? How does that experience carry over into your new role?</span></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">I’ve been the senior marketing guy at a number of tech startups, several of which really took off, and some of which...didn’t. Every one was a valuable learning experience, and all of them feel now like they were a dress rehearsal for my job at LeasePilot. We’ve got an opportunity to do something really great here, helping lots of companies save time and money in the leasing process.</span>\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Every new job comes with its own unique challenges. What’s priority #1 for you?</span></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">There are so many great things to say about LeasePilot and its underlying technology. I think the most important thing I can do as I get started here is to help craft a way of describing our value that’s quick, and that really connects, in a visceral way, with the people and companies we have an opportunity to serve. Or to put it another way, my goal is to tell a story -- the LeasePilot story -- in the most effective way possible.</span>\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Who inspires you?</span></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">I’ve been lucky enough to work for, and learn from, some great people in my career, and I draw inspiration from them. On a more personal level, I’m a music nut, so I draw a lot of inspiration from people in that world: Keith Richards, Charlie Rich, Smokey Robinson, and Miles Davis are all inspirations, each for slightly different reasons. </span>\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Top-3 albums?</span></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Just three? I’ll go with: the Stones’ Exile on Main St., Dylan’s Highway 61 Revisited, and this playlist mashup I love of Radiohead’s In Rainbows and OK Computer.</span>\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Let’s get controversial: is a hot dog a sandwich? Why or why not?</span></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Can’t we all get along?</span>\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Eggs &amp; bacon or waffles &amp; pancakes?</span></h3>\r\n<span style="font-weight: 400;">Eggs &amp; bacon, clearly. I’ll take savory over sweet every time.</span>', 'Meet the New VP of Marketing', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '6979-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-05-31 15:13:20', '2018-05-31 19:13:20', '', 6979, 'http://leasepilot.dev.cc/blog/6979-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(7062, 1, '2018-05-31 15:18:40', '2018-05-31 19:18:40', 'Most CRE companies using outside counsel would jump at the chance to pay their lawyers a flat fee for every deal. Law firms, however, aren’t typically so enthusiastic about the idea. So how can you get your outside counsel on board with flat fees? One of our customers came up with a pretty clever solution:\r\n\r\nThey looked at their total spending on outside counsel in a 12-month period and divided it by the number of lease deals they closed in that time. To keep the math simple, let’s say they did 50 deals in a year and spent $500,000 on outside counsel, an average of $10,000 per deal.\r\n\r\nNext, they calculated the projected efficiency gains LeasePilot would bring to the outside counsel’s workflow, which amounted to about 35%, or $3,500 per deal. With these numbers in hand, they approached outside law firms with a proposal: the company would provide law firms with the LeasePilot software and pay a fixed fee of $8,250 per deal, which amounts to splitting the $3,500 savings between both parties.\r\n\r\nThe switch to a fixed fee structure was a no-brainer for all involved. The lawyers would be making more money by spending less time on each lease, and the company would save money on every deal (and get it done faster). The entire process was more predictable and everybody came out ahead. Who doesn’t love that?', 'How to get your outside counsel on flat fees (and have them love it).', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '6974-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-05-31 15:18:40', '2018-05-31 19:18:40', '', 6974, 'http://leasepilot.dev.cc/blog/6974-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
